  "prompt": "Which day can be the first and the last day of a century?",
  "response": "The first day of a century can be any day of the week, as it depends on the specific century in question. For example:\n\n- January 1, 1901, was a Tuesday.\n- January 1, 2001, was a Monday.\n\nThe last day of a century, however, follows a more predictable pattern. The last day of a century will always be December 31 of a year that is a multiple of 100 (e.g., 1900, 2000, 2100). \n\nTo determine the day of the week for the last day of a century:\n\n1. **Identify the year**: For example, 2000, 2100, 2200.\n2. **Use Zeller's Congruence or a similar method** to find the day of the week for December 31 of that year.\n\nUsing Zeller's Congruence, we find:\n- December 31, 2000, was a Sunday.\n- December 31, 2100, will be a Friday.\n- December 31, 2200, will be a Wednesday.\n\nGiven this, the day that can be both the first and the last day of a century must be a day that can occur on January 1 of any given century year and also on December 31 of any century year.\n\nBy examining historical and future century start and end dates, we find that **January 1 can be any day of the week**, but **December 31 of a century year can only be one of the following**:\n- Saturday (e.g., December 31, 1700)\n- Thursday (e.g., December 31, 1800)\n- Tuesday (e.g., December 31, 1900)\n- Sunday (e.g., December 31, 2000)\n- Friday (e.g., December 31, 2100)\n- Wednesday (e.g., December 31, 2200)\n\nThe only day that appears as a possible start day for a century and also as a possible end day for a century is **Sunday**. \n\nFor example:\n- January 1, 2001, was a Monday, but January 1, 2101, will be a Sunday.\n- December 31, 2000, was a Sunday.\n\nTherefore, the day that can be both the first and the last day of a century is a **Sunday**.",
